         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden ¶ 8/12/72. ¶  ¶ Will you allow me to remark, dear Prof Gray, that when I was residing on the baltic and North Sea (1840-1846) I had ample opportunities to see the clear distinctio...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">72.12.08</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Asa Gray</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Gray Herbarium Archives, Harvard University, Cambridge, Massachusetts.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">8/12/72.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Will you allow me to remark, dear Prof Gray, that when I was residing on the baltic and North Sea (1840-1846) I had ample opportunities to see the clear distinctions between <name key="Poa%20maritima">Poa maritima</name> and P. distans. The former is a stronger plant &amp; has a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">long creeping</hi>
               </seg> root, which however is easily severed by pulling the plant &amp; left in the sand. Possibly you have only one of the two on your coasts. You may be able to set this right for a new edition of your most valuable Manual.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A. <seg style="">Gray (1867), p. 628, synonyms under </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Heleochloa </seg>
                     <seg style="">section of </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Glyceria</seg>
                     <seg style="">. Gray commented that </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. distans</seg>
                     <seg style=""> was 'too like the last' </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">[G. maritima</seg>
                     <seg style="">].</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> Mr. Watson<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Sereno Watson.</p>
               </note> has kindly sent me a fragment of <name key="Galax%20aphylla">Galax aphylla</name> and <name key="Samolus%20ebracteatus">Samolus ebracteatus</name>. The former seems referable to <name key="Saxifrageae">Saxifrageae</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Report,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">Not identified.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> sent by Mr. Watson, seems to have not yet arrived. A few brief supplemental notes to my "tree list"<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B71.06.02.</p>
               </note> and "select plants"<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B72.13.02.</p>
               </note> would from you be most acceptable and publicly acknowledged.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">In his introduction to B76.12.04, M acknowledged using Gray's published works among others, and some entries are specifically attributed to 'Dr. Asa Gray', eg. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Vicia sitchensis</seg>, p. 254.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With the best wishes for the stability of your health and the progress of your glorious researches your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">What follows is on a separate sheet but was presumably sent in same letter.</p>
               </note>Melbourne bot Garden 8/12/72.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Private</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Long since, dear Professor, I ought to have written to you, but for a long time past I have been subjected to much annoyance here,<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The Board of Inquiry into the management of the Botanic Gardens.</p>
               </note> far more so than even our friend Hooker.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Joseph Hooker; see MacLeod (1974).</p>
               </note> Thus my time was largely wasted in merely defending my position, and almost all scientific work has come to a stand still.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Galax%20aphylla">Galax aphylla</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Poa%20distans">Poa distans</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Poa%20maritima">Poa maritima</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Samolus%20ebracteatus">Samolus ebracteatus</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Saxifrageae">Saxifrageae</name>
            </p>
